data.content:
Here are the idiomatic MSTest replacements:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any());                          // or CollectionAssert.AreNotEquivalent for non-empty

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);          // if nulls matter
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));           // ✅ All() is fine here—no built-in equivalent

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3);
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);                     // gives "Expected:3, Actual:5" on failure

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null);
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsTrue(x.Any())` or `CollectionAssert.Contains` | Clearer intent |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Failure message shows expected vs actual |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer failure message |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` members:**
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)` — item exists
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order & elements
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, any order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)` — no duplicates

The general rule: prefer specific assertions (`AreEqual`, `IsNotNull`, `Contains`) over `Assert.IsTrue` because they produce **descriptive failure messages** instead of just "Expected: True, Actual: False".
